<DOC><DOCNO> AP890324-0164 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1833EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-24 0455</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0465</SECOND><HEAD>Soaking Rain Along East Coast, Light Rain On West Coast</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Rain fell over much of the northern half of the East Coast onFriday, with freezing rain and snow in some inland spots, and lightrain fell over much of the West Coast.   The low pressure system that dropped heavy rain along thecentral Gulf Coast earlier in the week slid up the East Coast andduring the afternoon rain was widespread from Maryland and easternVirginia to New York state and central New England.   The heaviest rain in the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST was 0.98 ofan inch at Fort Eustis, Va., the National Weather Service reported.   The clouds and rain kept temperatures in the 30s and 40s fromNew England to Virginia, with readings in the 50s over theCarolinas and Georgia.   In upstate New York, freezing rain was reported in theSusquehanna and Catskill regions and Binghamton reported freezingrain throughout most of the day.   Snow and sleet were scattered over parts of western New Englandand eastern New York, but temperatures were mostly above freezing.Two to 4 inches of snow was forecast for the mountains of Maine andNew Hampshire.   Gusty northeasterly wind blew across sections of the New Jerseycoast during the afternoon and gusts to 45 mph were reported aroundNew York City. Gale warnings were posted for the New Jersey coastand Long Island Sound.   A moist Pacific weather system spread rain throughout much ofthe West Coast states, but most rainfall amounts were less than aquarter inch. Snow was reported above 7,000 feet in the SierraNevada range, with accumulation of 6 to 12 inches possible aroundthe Lake Tahoe area.   In the middle of the nation, a few rain and snow showers spreadover the Dakotas and Minnesota.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 28degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 84 at Fort Myers, Fla. Friday's lowin the Lower 48 states was 2 degrees below zero at Houlton, Maine.   For Saturday, showers were forecast in the early part of the dayover New England, New York state and western Pennsylvania. Widelyscattered showers were forecast over southern Texas, and across thenorthern Plains and northern Rockies. Widespread rain was forecastover the West Coast states, and northern and central sections ofthe Intermountain region betwwen the Sierra Nevada and the Rockies.   Highs in the 40s and 50s were predicted from the PacificNorthwest across the northern Rockies, the northern Plains, theupper Mississippi Valley and the Great Lakes to New England; in the80s over Florida, Louisiana, Texas and southern Arizona; and in the60s and 70s elsewhere.</TEXT></DOC>